Yes, but in 2.7+ you can use definite assignment assertion to pretend the ref is non-null:

```ts
class Foo extends React.Component {
  elem!: HTMLInputElement;

  render() {
    return <input ref={elem => elem && (this.elem = elem)} />;
  }

  componentDidMount() {
    this.elem.focus();
  }
}
```

No such recourse will exist with `current` if it's nullable. Also, if people want to opt in to a nullable ref they can do so:

```ts
class Foo extends React.Component {
  ref = React.createRef<HTMLInputElement | null>();

  render() {
    return <input ref={this.ref} />;
  }
}
```

But if it's required to be nullable in the definition, they are unable to opt out.

